"{\"uid\": \"si.com-golf-2024-olympics-schauffele-fleetwood-matsuyama-share-lead-impassioned-fans\", \"text\": \"SAINT QUENTIN-EN-YVELINES, France \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 The French and English might not always be on the best of terms, famously known for not getting along, especially when it comes to sports.  But Tommy Fleetwood said Hideki Matsuyama jokingly wondered about his nationality given all the support the Englishman was getting on Friday from a predominantly French audience during the second round of the Olympic Golf Tournament.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt's been great,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 said Fleetwood, who despite a bogey on the final hole holds a share of the lead with Matsuyama and Xander Schauffele. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThe crowd has been absolutely amazing. It's a different set of supporters than what we get week-in and week-out.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt's a very Olympic crowd and atmosphere and it's been great. I always consider myself very lucky with the support I get but they have been amazing out there. Wyndham (Clark) and Hideki, both\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094so that was sweet. They have been great with me.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099  Shop: Get the best prices on golf rangefinders through SI Golf's retail partners  Fleetwood\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 7-under-par 64 put him in position to earn a medal this weekend at Le Golf National, where the PGA Tour and DP World Tour won player the French Open in 2017 and starred in the Ryder Cup in 2018.  His only blemish was that bogey on 18, a hole that promises to be interesting over the weekend. The hole has caused it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s share of fits. Matsuyama made a double-bogey there to fall into a tie with Schauffele, who added a 66 tohis opening 65.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt was a sad ending, but I am glad that today was only the second day,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 said Matsuyama, the 2021 Masters champion who missed out on a bronze medal in Japan three years ago when he lost in a playoff. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI think it means I need to change my mindset for the third day. I was glad I was able to get birdies.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099  That trio has played 36 holes in 131, 11 under par on a relatively benign course that is playing soft. They will be in the same group that tees off at 12:39 p.m. local time (6:39 a.m. ET) on Saturday.  Jon Rahm, with a 66, pulled within two shots of the leaders. Belgium\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Thomas Detry, Chinese Taipei\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s C.T. Pan (who won bronze in 2021) and South Korea\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Tom Kim are another shot back.  Scottie Scheffler is on the fringe of contention in a tie for 10th\\u00c2\\u00a0and five strokes behind the leaders while Rory McIlroy will have to come from six behind.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt's a great atmosphere to play in,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 McIlroy said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt's awesome, just the enthusiasm of the crowd is great.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099  There are 18 players within six shots of the lead.  Not much has gotten in Schauffele\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s way of late, so perhaps he was due for some interference from nature.  A pile of ants, of all things, sent Schauffele on his way to a rare bogey. And not even that managed to knock him out of a share of the lead.  Schauffele, the reigning gold medal winner fresh off a win at the British Open, encountered his issue at the par-4 13th\\u00c2\\u00a0hole where he hit his ball in the rough and noticed something behind it.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI was kind of putting my club down and sort of that fluffy sort of\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094fluffy grass almost, and I am taking practice swings and I am trying to get to my ball and I can not even . . . what's going on, something is behind my ball.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI went down and saw a pile, so I called an official. It was just ants. It was a pile of ants, an ant pile, or whatever you want to call it, and their home; so I did not want to mess with it. Could not take relief. It's a loose impediment.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099  Schauffele sought the advise of two rules officials who said he could not be given a drop in that situation but could remove the ants from behind the ball.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI did not do anything to be honest,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 Schauffele said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI ended up hacking out 50 yards on the fairway.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099  That led to his second bogey of the day but he rebounded with a birdie at the next hole and parred his way in.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWhen you are in good form, all of us know that it's all about just making the correct decision and executing the shot and rinse and repeating that process,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 Schauffele said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSo do not let too much try and bother you, and if you do hit a bad shots, it's easier to accept it because you know you are playing really good golf and you can make it up somewhere else. In that sort of zone, I guess.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099  For Fleetwood, an Olympic victory could be considered the best of his career. He has yet to win on the PGA Tour and has come close in a few major championships. He's currently ranked 14th\\u00c2\\u00a0in the world and won in January at the Dubai Invitational. But he has just two top-10s since, one of them a tie for third at the Masters.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI actually have not been in contention for a while,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 Fleetwood said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI kind of enjoy that on its own, as well as it being the Olympics.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cLike I say, it brings with it its own mental challenges. You are playing for a medal. You look at the atmosphere this week, we constantly get asked the question, where does the Olympics sit in golf. When you look at how it's going this week, it continues and continues to grow, and what people feel about it. It brings its own nerves and excitement and it's very, very special. So it's its own unique feeling and it's amazing.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Bob Harig is a senior writer covering golf for Sports Illustrated. He has more than 25 years experience on the beat, including 15 at ESPN. Harig is a regular guest on Sirius XM PGA Tour Radio and has written two books, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cDRIVE: The Lasting Legacy of Tiger Woods\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d and \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cTiger and Phil: Golf\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Most Fascinating Rivalry.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d He graduated from Indiana University where he earned an Evans Scholarship, named in honor of the great amateur golfer Charles (Chick) Evans Jr. Harig, a former president of the Golf Writers Association of America, lives in Clearwater, Fla.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"